      Turquoise Hill
   =20
 =20

The general rule in mergers and acquisitions is that if you want to buy a c=
ompany you have to pay all the shareholders the same price. This is not an=
=C2=A0absolute=C2=A0rule. You can buy some shares of the company at varying=
=C2=A0market prices before you decide to buy the whole thing at a fixed pri=
ce, as Elon Musk did with Twitter Inc.
  [1]
=C2=A0Shareholders of the company who are also=C2=A0executives=C2=A0can get=
 paid more than regular shareholders, in the form of employment contracts o=
r severance pay. Shareholders with special classes of shares that get more =
votes can get paid more for those votes. But for the most part you are not =
allowed to=C2=A0simply=C2=A0say, like, =E2=80=9Cwe will pay 51% of sharehol=
ders $40 per share, and the other 49% $1 per share,=E2=80=9D and then get t=
he 51% of shareholders to approve the deal and stiff the 49%.
  [2]
=C2=A0
But like I said this is not an absolute rule, and sometimes you will want t=
o give a few noisy shareholders a little nudge to get a deal done. In Musk=
=E2=80=99s deal for Twitter, for instance, one shareholder =E2=80=94 Saudi=
=C2=A0Prince Alwaleed bin Talal=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0complained that Musk=E2=
=80=99s bid of $54.20 per share did not =E2=80=9Ccome close to the intrinsi=
c value=E2=80=9D of Twitter. (This was in April, when that was a plausible =
position.) Alwaleed=E2=80=99s Kingdom Holding Co. owned about 4.6% of Twitt=
er, and you could imagine him voting against the deal and making it less li=
kely to go through.   Musk solved this problem by allowing Kingdom to roll =
its Twitter shares into the privately owned company, an offer that was exte=
nded to some other big Twitter shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0including Jack D=
orsey =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not all of them. Big noisy shareholders who were e=
ither (1) friendly with Musk or (2)=C2=A0antagonistic=C2=A0to Musk in a way=
 that might block the deal were offered the chance to keep their stock in M=
usk=E2=80=99s private Twitter. Ordinary retail shareholders were not: They =
just got to vote for or against the deal, and if enough of them voted for i=
t then they=E2=80=99d all get cashed out at $54.20. They did, and they were=
, and given subsequent events none of them are really complaining.
In fact, this is not uncommon in going-private transactions, allowing some =
shareholders to roll over into the private company. If some big shareholder=
 likes the stock and is willing to take a minority stake in the private com=
pany,=C2=A0that is often helpful for the acquirer, since it reduces the acq=
uirer=E2=80=99s need for cash and increases the chances of getting the deal=
 approved.=C2=A0
What you=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0really do=C2=A0is give a few big noisy sha=
reholders=C2=A0extra cash=C2=A0to get them to vote for the deal. That just =
seems straightforwardly unfair.=C2=A0
On the other hand! Turquoise Hill Resources Ltd. is a Canadian mining compa=
ny that is 51% owned by Rio Tinto International Holdings Ltd. Rio Tinto wan=
ts to buy the remaining 49% of Turquoise Hill for C$43 per share. Turquoise=
 Hill=E2=80=99s board appointed a special committee of independent director=
s, which=C2=A0approved the transaction at that price, and submitted it to a=
 shareholder vote. To get approved, the deal requires (1) a two-thirds vote=
 of all shares (which is easy since Rio owns 51%)=C2=A0and also (2) a major=
ity vote of the non-Rio shareholders. Two big shareholders, Pentwater Capit=
al Management LP and SailingStone Capital Partners LLC, don=E2=80=99t like =
the deal and want more money. If they voted against the deal, Rio might not=
 win.=C2=A0
And so Rio struck a deal with them, which Turquoise Hill somewhat passive-a=
ggressively  announced today.=C2=A0(Here are the  actual  agreements.) The =
shareholders agreed not to vote one way or the other on the merger, which m=
akes it easier to get a majority vote of the non-Rio shares. (The deal=C2=
=A0only needs a majority of the non-Rio shares=C2=A0that vote=C2=A0to vote =
yes, so abstaining does not count as a no vote.) In exchange, Rio agreed to=
 pay them 80% of the merger price (C$34.40) at closing, and then go to arbi=
tration over how much the company is worth. If Rio wins the arbitration it =
will give them the remaining 20% (C$8.60), plus interest, meaning that they=
 do as well as the regular shareholders who are cashed out at C$43. If Rio =
loses, it will pay them more, basically whatever the arbitrator decides is =
the fair value of Turquoise Hill.
This seems like a better deal than the public shareholders are getting. Pub=
lic shareholders can either (1)=C2=A0approve the deal and take the C$43 wit=
h no upside, (2)=C2=A0reject the deal=C2=A0and then have minority shares in=
 a controlled public company that are worth whatever the market says they=
=E2=80=99re worth, or (3) approve the deal, but individual shareholders who=
 vote no can=C2=A0seek =E2=80=9Cdissent rights=E2=80=9D (called =E2=80=9Cap=
praisal rights=E2=80=9D in the US), meaning that they get  whatever a court=
 decides is the fair value of the stock, but possibly less than C$43. But P=
entwater and SailingStone are guaranteed C$43 and have some upside and a fr=
iendlier process for determining that upside.
That is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0unusual, and a bit aggressive? Turquoise Hill  think=
s so:
The Special Committee was first advised of the potential terms of the Agree=
ments on the evening of Sunday, October 30, 2022. The Special Committee sug=
gested to Rio Tinto that it offer comparable dissent proceedings as those o=
ffered to the Named Shareholders in the Agreements to all holders of Minori=
ty Shares (the =E2=80=9CMinority Shareholders=E2=80=9D). Rio Tinto advised =
that it was not making the terms of the Agreements available to all Minorit=
y Shareholders.=C2=A0
Ah. Well. I think that if Rio just offered to pay Pentwater and Sailingston=
e an extra $5 per share, the special committee would have done more than =
=E2=80=9Csuggest=E2=80=9D offering it to everyone. But if you punt this to =
arbitration where Rio=C2=A0might=C2=A0pay an extra $5 per share, that might=
 just work.

