   =20
      Distress
   =20
 =20

In debt, the rule is different. We have   talked a few times about what I t=
hink of as the general theory of modern distressed debt investing, and to o=
versimplify it only slightly, that theory is =E2=80=9Cpay 51% of creditors =
a lot of money, pay the other 49% zero, and get the 51% to vote to stiff th=
e 49%.=E2=80=9D Exactly what is not allowed in mergers. People don=E2=80=99=
t like it that much in debt either.
The standard story goes like this. A company has a bunch of debt outstandin=
g. It is running into trouble and needs more money to operate, or more time=
 to pay back its debt, or both. It looks carefully into its debt documents =
and realizes that it can change the terms of its debt, as long as holders o=
f a majority (or sometimes a supermajority, perhaps two-thirds) of the debt=
 agree.
It can=E2=80=99t change the terms=C2=A0too=C2=A0much =E2=80=94=C2=A0it can=
=E2=80=99t reduce the amount of the debt or the interest rate, or push back=
 the maturity date, without consent from=C2=A0every=C2=A0creditor=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but it can do some important things. In particular, it can tink=
er with the seniority of the debt. A company might have secured debt outsta=
nding that says things like =E2=80=9Cthis debt has a first-lien claim to al=
l of the company=E2=80=99s assets=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe company can=E2=
=80=99t issue any new debt that is senior to this debt.=E2=80=9D And a majo=
rity (or supermajority) vote might allow the company to move some of its as=
sets into a new subsidiary, make that subsidiary not part of the collateral=
 for the existing debt, and then issue new debt secured by that subsidiary=
=E2=80=99s assets. In practice the company can issue new debt that is senio=
r to its existing debt, even though the existing debt is supposed to be the=
 most senior debt.
And then the company goes to some of its lenders
  [3]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0enough of them to vote to approve the amendments =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and says =E2=80=9Chey, we will create new good debt, and make o=
ur old debt bad. If you (1) vote to approve this and (2) lend us some more =
money, we will turn both your new money and your existing loans into good d=
ebt, and we will leave all the=C2=A0other=C2=A0lenders with the bad debt.=
=E2=80=9D The favored lenders will get good debt in exchange for putting in=
 more money and approving the amendments. The other lenders will watch as t=
heir good debt gets turned into bad debt.
And then one of two things happens. (Well, first the other lenders will sue=
, but we=E2=80=99ll get to that.)
=09Perhaps this will work. The company will survive, the extra money will b=
e enough to fix the problems, it will avoid bankruptcy, and everyone will e=
ventually get paid back. The favored lenders will have a better time of it,=
 but everyone will eventually get their money.=09Perhaps it won=E2=80=99t w=
ork and the company will go bankrupt anyway. Then the favored lenders =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0whose debt is now secured by good assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0will mo=
re or less get paid, and the disfavored lenders more or less won=E2=80=99t.=
=C2=A0

Now, at this point, everyone in the market is aware of this stuff. So when =
a company starts running into distress, and starts making the sorts of nois=
es and hiring the sorts of advisers that indicate it might do this sort of =
thing, there will be a race to buy up its debt. You want to have, or be in =
a group of lenders who have, a majority of the debt, so that you can be on =
the winning side of this trade rather than the losing side. Or if the debt =
requires a supermajority to do this trade, you want to acquire (or have you=
r group of lenders acquire) a blocking position, at least one-third of the =
debt, so that the company can=E2=80=99t do this without your permission.
One result of this is that sometimes the debt of a very distressed company =
will trade at very high prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps over 100 cents on the=
 dollar =E2=80=94=C2=A0because that debt is in high demand to do or block t=
his sort of transaction; it is worth overpaying for some of this debt to av=
oid being stiffed on=C2=A0the rest of your position.
Another result is that sometimes the company won=E2=80=99t have a majority =
(or supermajority) to do the transaction: Its favored lenders will have 40%=
, or 55%, of the debt, and it will need 51% or 67%. But there is a fix to t=
hat: Issue more debt. If the existing debt has some provision allowing the =
company to issue more of it, you just issue more of it to the favored lende=
rs, until they have 51% or 67% or whatever. Then they vote for the amendmen=
t and roll their new debt into the even newer, favored debt.
Both of these results are economically weird. A company will get into distr=
ess, its debt will trade at 40 or 60 cents on the dollar, and then it will =
spike up to 105 as people race to get control. And then it will fall back t=
o 40 or 60, and the company will issue more of it at 100, as it tries to li=
ne up the right number of votes. In simple economic terms you would not pay=
 100 or 105 cents on the dollar for this sort of distressed debt, but to ge=
t control of a transaction like this, people do.
There are two recent lawsuits in cases like this, arguing that these transa=
ctions =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly, issuing new debt to get enough votes =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0were =E2=80=9Cshams=E2=80=9D and should be reversed by court=
s.   One is about the Incora case, which we   talked about back in April. (=
Incora is, somehow, the name of a company called Wesco Aircraft Holdings In=
c.? Don=E2=80=99t ask.) There, the company needed a two-thirds vote to appr=
ove changes to the debt. There were two groups of creditors, and they raced=
 to buy the debt, causing it to trade up to 105 cents on the dollar. From  =
the complaint:
A bidding war ensued as both sides attempted to ensure they would have the =
necessary amount of 2026 Senior Secured Notes to either block such a=C2=A0t=
ransaction in the case of Plaintiffs or form a two-thirds supermajority in =
the case of the Favored Noteholders. As reflected in the chart below, the 2=
026 Senior Secured Notes and 2024 Senior Secured Notes were both trading at=
 roughly 85 cents on the dollar on February 7, 2022, when rumors of a poten=
tial transaction first leaked. By early March 2022, the market price of 202=
6 Senior Secured Notes reached 105 cents on the dollar, far above their int=
rinsic value.
The minority group won the race and got more than one-third of the bonds, p=
reventing the restructuring transaction. But the company did it anyway, by =
issuing new notes and getting their consent:

Defendants executed (or consented to) unauthorized amendments to the Govern=
ing Indentures that resulted in the issuance of new notes to certain Favore=
d Noteholders for the specific purpose of diluting Plaintiffs=E2=80=99 bloc=
king position in the 2026 Senior Secured Notes and obtaining a feigned supe=
rmajority. Those new notes were issued to those Favored Noteholders for no =
purpose other than to gerrymander a vote of the 2026 Senior Secured Notes, =
and once that vote occurred, the new notes were exchanged and cancelled on =
the same day they were issued. =E2=80=A6
The fleeting existence of the Phantom Notes confirms that their only purpos=
e was to subvert Plaintiffs=E2=80=99 supermajority consent rights and illus=
trates the integrated nature of the agreements comprising the Sham Transact=
ion. For example, no rational economic noteholder would have voted the Phan=
tom Notes against their interests to immediately strip themselves of their =
security interests in the Collateral=E2=80=94as was done through the Fourth=
 Supplemental Indenture=E2=80=94without that noteholder being assured that =
the Phantom Notes would immediately be exchanged for New 1L Notes. Likewise=
, no rational investor would have purchased the Phantom Notes but for the C=
ompany=E2=80=99s promise to simultaneously exchange them for the New 1L Not=
es. Indeed, upon information and belief, the Phantom Notes were purchased b=
y Favored Notedholders at or near par=C2=A0while otherwise identical 2026 S=
enior Secured Notes were trading at approximately 84 cents.

 The other is about Revlon Inc., the bankrupt cosmetics maker, which we hav=
e   talked about a   lot because Citigroup Inc. messed up Revlon=E2=80=99s =
restructuring=C2=A0transaction in an embarrassing way. But there the restru=
cturing required majority consent, and they didn=E2=80=99t have a majority,=
 so they created one. From  the complaint:

The Conspiring Lenders held only a minority of that debt=E2=80=94they could=
 not consent to an amendment on their own. And they faced united opposition=
 from a group of more than 50% of the 2016 Term Lenders, who entered into a=
 joint cooperation agreement and made clear they would oppose Defendants=E2=
=80=99 proposed amendments (the =E2=80=9CCo-Op Lenders=E2=80=9D).
Undeterred, RCPC and the Conspiring Lenders tried to devise an end-run arou=
nd the 2016 Credit Agreement=E2=80=99s consent requirements: RCPC=E2=80=94w=
ith Citibank=E2=80=99s assistance (as Administrative and Collateral Agent)=
=E2=80=94would issue new, unfunded revolver commitments (not real loans, ju=
st illusory commitments) under the 2016 Credit Agreement to the Conspiring =
Lenders. RCPC and the Conspiring Lenders then claimed that these new =E2=80=
=9Ccommitments=E2=80=9D would increase the Conspiring Lenders=E2=80=99 voti=
ng rights such that they would have a voting majority. And, reflecting its =
intent to manipulate lender voting, RCPC planned to obtain the exact amount=
 of commitments necessary to purportedly inch over a 50.0% consent threshol=
d. =E2=80=A6
Indeed, no rational lender would have lent new bona fide money to RCPC unde=
r the 2016 Credit Agreement=E2=80=94the 2016 Term Loans were trading at aro=
und 43 cents on the dollar and were certain to move much lower if the trans=
action went through. And, in fact, no lender did. Rather, Revlon and the Co=
nspiring Lenders arranged for these new revolver =E2=80=9Cloans=E2=80=9D to=
 be replaced by the soon-to-be-issued loans under the new BrandCo debt faci=
lities, all secured by the BrandCo IP. In fact, exactly fifteen days after =
they were issued, the Sham Revolver commitments disappeared. These revolver=
 =E2=80=9Cloans=E2=80=9D served no legitimate business purpose; rather, the=
ir sole purpose was to manipulate consent thresholds and disenfranchise the=
 majority 2016 Term Lenders so that Defendants could consummate their schem=
e to divest the 2016 Term Lenders of their firstpriority liens on the Brand=
Co IP.

The basic question in these cases is: Can you just read the debt documents =
as craftily as possible, do whatever is strictly allowed by the text, and b=
enefit some creditors at the expense of others? Or is there some background=
 requirement of fairness or =E2=80=9Coh come on it can=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0=
meant=C2=A0that,=E2=80=9D so that your craftiest readings don=E2=80=99t act=
ually work? The traditional view is that shareholders are entitled to fiduc=
iary duties =E2=80=94=C2=A0which is why mergers have to be more or less fai=
r to all shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0while creditors are entitled only to t=
he letter of their contract. That traditional view has given rise to, you k=
now, all this: a whole industry of distressed-debt cleverness built on stru=
cturing transactions to exploit the documents as much as possible. I suppos=
e it is possible to take it too far, though: If creditors get too good at r=
uthlessly exploiting each other, eventually courts might step in and say =
=E2=80=9Coh come on it can=E2=80=99t have meant that.=E2=80=9D If a rule li=
ke =E2=80=9Ccreditors are only entitled to what their contract explicitly s=
ays=E2=80=9D always leads to absurd results, it might stop being the rule.

