   =20
      Borrow long to lend short
   =20
 =20

If you have a roughly-one-year-ago-vintage mortgage, you should  probably n=
ever move:

Some lucky Americans are earning a higher interest rate on their high-yield=
 savings accounts than they=E2=80=99re paying on their mortgage. =E2=80=A6
There were 4.2 million mortgaged homes =E2=80=94 8% of the total =E2=80=94 =
with a current rate of 2.5% or lower as of the end of September, according =
to Black Knight, a mortgage technology and data provider.
These people either locked in a mortgage or refinanced before rates started=
 to surge. They=E2=80=99re in the brag-worthy position of paying the same o=
r less in interest than they could be earning on a high-yield savings accou=
nt at Goldman Sachs Group Inc.=E2=80=99s Marcus, which recently hiked its r=
ate to a record 2.5%.
By comparison, the average rate for a 30-year, fixed mortgage has more than=
 doubled this year and last week moved north of 7% for the first time in mo=
re than two decades. That=E2=80=99s deterred potential buyers, with prices =
falling from their peaks and sales plummeting.=C2=A0

Disclosure, I have a fairly cheap 30-year fixed-rate mortgage and a Marcus =
account, and I am not sure I have much of a point here other than to mentio=
n=C2=A0that. =E2=80=9CMortgages have negative convexity because their durat=
ion goes up as interest rates go up, since nobody wants to prepay, refinanc=
e or move when rates are high,=E2=80=9D is a thing that I could have told y=
ou a year ago, but then it was of sort of academic interest to me. Now I am=
 living it.

 =20
   =20
      Good severance
   =20
 =20

One funny thing that could happen to you is that your employer could promis=
e to pay you $680,000 over 16 months, meaning about $42,500 per month, but =
then in the contract, instead of typing =E2=80=9Cwe will pay you $680,000 i=
n monthly installments over 16 months,=E2=80=9D they might type =E2=80=9Cwe=
 will pay you $680,000 per month for 16 months.=E2=80=9D That would be bett=
er, for you, though you=E2=80=99d definitely have to go to court about it. =
Here is  law professor Jeff Lipshaw=C2=A0on a real case:

A Chinese tech company has a U.S. subsidiary. =C2=A0The subsidiary hires a =
senior executive on a fixed term three-year contract. =C2=A0Along the way, =
the parent company=E2=80=99s founder in China, wants the executive fired. =
=C2=A0Negotiations for the separation ensue, in English and in Mandarin, bu=
t the contract is in English, drafted by the subsidiary=E2=80=99s outside l=
awyers in Virginia. =C2=A0Drafts get circulated internally, but it=E2=80=99=
s clear that the executive, at the very least, is going to get the balance =
of his salary for the remainder of the three-year contract: =E2=80=9CThe Co=
mpany agrees to make severance payments to you in the form of continuation =
of your base salary in effect on the Separation Date for sixteen (16) month=
s.=E2=80=9D =C2=A0That total would have been $680,000.
Then things go terribly wrong (internally). =C2=A0The outside lawyer change=
s the draft to this: =E2=80=9C[T]he Company agrees to make monthly severanc=
e payments to you in the amount of $ _____ for sixteen (16) months.=E2=80=
=9D =C2=A0The in-house gets the drafts and types into the blank =E2=80=9C$6=
80,000=E2=80=9D, creating a putative obligation of $10,880,000.

This went to court and, as of last month, the executive won =E2=80=94 he ge=
ts the $11 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0though that could still be appealed.=C2=
=A0

 =20
   =20
      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

I am not going to write much about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s plan to charge users=
 of Twitter $8 a month for some vague set of upgrades, but lots of other pe=
ople have. My favorite might be=C2=A0Ben Thompson=E2=80=99s=C2=A0rather bea=
rish post, which argues essentially that Twitter is a very unpleasant produ=
ct that most people do not want to use, but is extremely appealing and addi=
ctive to a small minority of us with significant personality flaws. This ma=
kes it a bad advertising business (not enough scale), but possibly a good s=
ubscription business (extremely addictive). I don=E2=80=99t really disagree=
 with him but it is depressing.

