  [1] Though he   broke the law a little bit in doing it: The law requires =
him to disclose his ownership in Twitter once it got above 5%, precisely be=
cause that disclosure would alert everyone to his interest in buying the wh=
ole company, and might make people stop selling to you at market prices. Mu=
sk delayed that legally required disclosure, which allowed him to buy more =
stock cheaply.


  [2] I am asserting this as a general rule of thumb, not a legal doctrine.=
 In the US, the legal doctrine sort of comes from two places. One is the ru=
les about tender offers, and particularly the doctrine of a =E2=80=9Ccreepi=
ng tender=E2=80=9D: Generally if you are trying to buy all of a company=E2=
=80=99s stock in the market, you have disclosure and fairness requirements.=
 Another is the board of directors' fiduciary duties to all shareholders: I=
f you are trying to buy a company in a merger (rather than a tender offer),=
 you have to negotiate with the board, and the board is not going to agree =
to give a different deal to different shareholders, because they will get s=
ued. In particular there is a lot of Delaware law from the 1980s heyday of =
hostile takeovers where boards said =E2=80=9Cwe worry that this acquirer wi=
ll get a majority of the stock and then freeze out minority shareholders at=
 a lower price, so we are putting in place a poison pill to block the acqui=
sition,=E2=80=9D and courts were sympathetic to that.


  [3] Or the lenders go to the company; there=E2=80=99s a vigorous market f=
or this stuff, and you want to be proactive about being on the winning side=
.


