<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Turquoise Hill</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The general rule in mergers and acquisitions i=
s that if you want to buy a company you have to pay all the shareholders th=
e same price. This is not an=C2=A0<em>absolute=C2=A0</em>rule. You can buy =
some shares of the company at varying=C2=A0market prices before you decide =
to buy the whole thing at a fixed price, as Elon Musk did with Twitter Inc.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Shareholders of the company who are also=C2=A0executives<em>=C2=
=A0</em>can get paid more than regular shareholders, in the form of employm=
ent contracts or severance pay. Shareholders with special classes of shares=
 that get more votes can get paid more for those votes. But for the most pa=
rt you are not allowed to=C2=A0<em>simply=C2=A0</em>say, like, =E2=80=9Cwe =
will pay 51% of shareholders $40 per share, and the other 49% $1 per share,=
=E2=80=9D and then get the 51% of shareholders to approve the deal and stif=
f the 49%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But like I said this is not an absolute rule, =
and sometimes you will want to give a few noisy shareholders a little nudge=
 to get a deal done. In Musk=E2=80=99s deal for Twitter, for instance, one =
shareholder =E2=80=94 Saudi=C2=A0Prince Alwaleed bin Talal=C2=A0=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0complained that Musk=E2=80=99s bid of $54.20 per share did not =E2=80=
=9Ccome close to the intrinsic value=E2=80=9D of Twitter. (This was in Apri=
l, when that was a plausible position.) Alwaleed=E2=80=99s Kingdom Holding =
Co. owned about 4.6% of Twitter, and you could imagine him voting against t=
he deal and making it less likely to go through. <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29572408.263505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMDkvbXVzay10d2l0dGVyLWhhcy1uZXctb3d=
uZXJzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7fb64ff4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Musk solved this problem</a> by =
allowing Kingdom to roll its Twitter shares into the privately owned compan=
y, an offer that was extended to some other big Twitter shareholders =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0including Jack Dorsey =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not all of them. Big nois=
y shareholders who were either (1) friendly with Musk or (2)=C2=A0<em>antag=
onistic=C2=A0</em>to Musk in a way that might block the deal were offered t=
he chance to keep their stock in Musk=E2=80=99s private Twitter. Ordinary r=
etail shareholders were not: They just got to vote for or against the deal,=
 and if enough of them voted for it then they=E2=80=99d all get cashed out =
at $54.20. They did, and they were, and given subsequent events none of the=
m are really complaining.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, this is not uncommon in going-private=
 transactions, allowing some shareholders to roll over into the private com=
pany. If some big shareholder likes the stock and is willing to take a mino=
rity stake in the private company,=C2=A0that is often helpful for the acqui=
rer, since it reduces the acquirer=E2=80=99s need for cash and increases th=
e chances of getting the deal approved.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What you=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>real=
ly do=C2=A0is give a few big noisy shareholders=C2=A0<em>extra cash=C2=A0</=
em>to get them to vote for the deal. That just seems straightforwardly unfa=
ir.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand! Turquoise Hill Resources Lt=
d. is a Canadian mining company that is 51% owned by Rio Tinto Internationa=
l Holdings Ltd. Rio Tinto wants to buy the remaining 49% of Turquoise Hill =
for C$43 per share. Turquoise Hill=E2=80=99s board appointed a special comm=
ittee of independent directors, which=C2=A0approved the transaction at that=
 price, and submitted it to a shareholder vote. To get approved, the deal r=
equires (1) a two-thirds vote of all shares (which is easy since Rio owns 5=
1%)=C2=A0<em>and also </em>(2) a majority vote of the non-Rio shareholders.=
 Two big shareholders, Pentwater Capital Management LP and SailingStone Cap=
ital Partners LLC, don=E2=80=99t like the deal and want more money. If they=
 voted against the deal, Rio might not win.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so Rio struck a deal with them, which Turq=
uoise Hill somewhat passive-aggressively <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/29572408.263505/aHR0cHM6Ly90dXJxdW9pc2VoaWxsLmNvbS9p=
bnZlc3RvcnMvbmV3cy9uZXdzLWRldGFpbHMvMjAyMi9UdXJxdW9pc2UtSGlsbC1BY2tub3dsZWR=
nZXMtQW5ub3VuY2VtZW50LWJ5LVJpby1UaW50by1vZi1BZ3JlZW1lbnRzLXdpdGgtQ2VydGFpbi=
1NaW5vcml0eS1TaGFyZWhvbGRlcnMtb2YtVHVycXVvaXNlLUhpbGwvZGVmYXVsdC5hc3B4/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafffcb37" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> announced today</a>.=C2=A0(Here are=
 the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29572408.2635=
05/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg2MzA2NC8wMDAxMTkz=
MTI1MjIyNzUxOTAvZDM5OTU4MGRleDk5Yi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB816d2422" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> actual</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/29572408.263505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg2M=
zA2NC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjIyNzUxOTAvZDM5OTU4MGRleDk5YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBd45ab5dc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> agreements</a>.) The shareholders agreed not to vot=
e one way or the other on the merger, which makes it easier to get a majori=
ty vote of the non-Rio shares. (The deal=C2=A0only needs a majority of the =
non-Rio shares=C2=A0<em>that vote=C2=A0</em>to vote yes, so abstaining does=
 not count as a no vote.) In exchange, Rio agreed to pay them 80% of the me=
rger price (C$34.40) at closing, and then go to arbitration over how much t=
he company is worth. If Rio wins the arbitration it will give them the rema=
ining 20% (C$8.60), plus interest, meaning that they do as well as the regu=
lar shareholders who are cashed out at C$43. If Rio loses, it will pay them=
 more, basically whatever the arbitrator decides is the fair value of Turqu=
oise Hill.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems like a better deal than the public =
shareholders are getting. Public shareholders can either (1)=C2=A0approve t=
he deal and take the C$43 with no upside, (2)=C2=A0reject the deal=C2=A0and=
 then have minority shares in a controlled public company that are worth wh=
atever the market says they=E2=80=99re worth, or (3) approve the deal, but =
individual shareholders who vote no can=C2=A0seek =E2=80=9Cdissent rights=
=E2=80=9D (called =E2=80=9Cappraisal rights=E2=80=9D in the US), meaning th=
at they get <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/295724=
08.263505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3c29ubHVuZGVsbC5jb20vdGhlLWJ1c2luZXNzLWxhdy1ib=
G9nL3l1a29uLWNvdXJ0LWF3YXJkcy1wcmVtaXVtLWluLWZhaXItdmFsdWU/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB654bd035" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> whatever a court decides</a> is the fair value =
of the stock, but possibly less than C$43. But Pentwater and SailingStone a=
re guaranteed C$43 and have some upside and a friendlier process for determ=
ining that upside.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0unusual, and a bit aggr=
essive? Turquoise Hill <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/29572408.263505/aHR0cHM6Ly90dXJxdW9pc2VoaWxsLmNvbS9pbnZlc3RvcnMvbmV3cy=
9uZXdzLWRldGFpbHMvMjAyMi9UdXJxdW9pc2UtSGlsbC1BY2tub3dsZWRnZXMtQW5ub3VuY2VtZ=
W50LWJ5LVJpby1UaW50by1vZi1BZ3JlZW1lbnRzLXdpdGgtQ2VydGFpbi1NaW5vcml0eS1TaGFy=
ZWhvbGRlcnMtb2YtVHVycXVvaXNlLUhpbGwvZGVmYXVsdC5hc3B4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cCafffcb37" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> thinks so</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Special Committee was first ad=
vised of the potential terms of the Agreements on the evening of Sunday, Oc=
tober 30, 2022. The Special Committee suggested to Rio Tinto that it offer =
comparable dissent proceedings as those offered to the Named Shareholders i=
n the Agreements to all holders of Minority Shares (the =E2=80=9CMinority S=
hareholders=E2=80=9D). Rio Tinto advised that it was not making the terms o=
f the Agreements available to all Minority Shareholders.=C2=A0</p></blockqu=
ote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah. Well. I think that if Rio just offered to =
pay Pentwater and Sailingstone an extra $5 per share, the special committee=
 would have done more than =E2=80=9Csuggest=E2=80=9D offering it to everyon=
e. But if you punt this to arbitration where Rio=C2=A0<em>might</em><em>=C2=
=A0</em>pay an extra $5 per share, that might just work.</p>
